"You know Nic, I just think you're lazy!"\
\
Those were the words of someone I had recently sought to have lunch with who I thought could help me. I was furious inside. No one worked as hard as I did since we had started the church. I was up at 5 in the morning and worked until it was dark many days. I only took one day off a week and many times that wasn't a full day to the dismay of my wife and kids. Who did this person think they were to tell me I was lazy...they had no clue and I was about to tell them.\
\
That is, until he clarified a few moments later. \
\
"I know you work really hard, I just think you're relationally lazy. You need to get out to meet more people. Quit holing up in your office and build relationships with others." \
\
I went from furious to focused really quick. While I was still hurting from even the notion of being lazy at all, there was some truth to what he saying to me. I had felt for a while that God was calling me to get out in the community more. To put myself out there be more available. But I hadn't up to that point. \
\
Honestly, I didn't want to. And it was easy to say I didn't have the time but that wasn't the issue. That was an excuse. Last time I checked we all have the same amount of time - 168 hours in the week. And to make it worse, as the lead pastor I set my own schedule so if my schedule was messed up then it was solely my fault. So what was the problem. \
\
I knew what I needed to do, I did have the time if I wanted to. I was just being...(it took everything in me to admit this)...lazy!\
\
He was right. I was only doing what I wanted to do, hiding behind a work schedule that was at break neck speed. \
\
\
